{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17235"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17235"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9925"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63112"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7618"},{"type":"tags","id":"7635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23276"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProtein synthesis in eukaryotic cells is a complex process requiring precise coordination between messenger RNA (mRNA), transfer RNA (tRNA), ribosomes and various protein factors. The process begins with a critical initiation phase that determines where protein synthesis will start.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first step of translation initiation in eukaryotic cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Assembly of initiation factors at the 5\u0027 cap structure","Scanning of mRNA by the small ribosomal subunit","Recognition of the AUG start codon","Binding of tRNA to the P site","Formation of the peptide bond"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first step of translation initiation in eukaryotes involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eassembly of initiation factors at the 5\u0027 cap structure\u003C/strong\u003E of the messenger RNA. This creates a platform for subsequent steps in the initiation process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent events that occur later in translation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScanning of mRNA by the small ribosomal subunit\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after initiation factors have assembled and recruited the 40S subunit\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecognition of the AUG start codon\u003C/strong\u003E happens during the scanning process when the initiation complex encounters the start codon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding of tRNA to the P site\u003C/strong\u003E requires prior assembly of the complete 80S ribosome at the start codon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of the peptide bond\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the elongation phase, occurring after initiation is complete\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ordered assembly of initiation factors at the 5\u0027 cap is essential for recruiting other components and ensuring translation begins at the correct location.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Translation initiation in eukaryotes requires the assembly of initiation factors, Met-tRNA, and ribosomal subunits at the 5\u0027 cap of mRNA.","The scanning model of translation involves movement of the initiation complex along mRNA until reaching the AUG start codon.","Recognition of the start codon triggers release of initiation factors and assembly of the complete ribosome to begin protein synthesis."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63112"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17235"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63112"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:14:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:18:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9925"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13: